<BaseLayout title="The K-Drama Restaurant Guide: Real Restaurants from Your Favourite Shows" description="The K-Drama Restaurant Guide — every real restaurant from your favourite Korean dramas, reviewed and rated. The Hansang.">

  <header class="article-header">
    <div class="article-pillar-tag"><a href="/culture/">Culture</a> &middot; K-Drama</div>
    <h1>The K-Drama Restaurant Guide: Real Restaurants from Your Favourite Shows</h1>
    <div class="article-byline">
      <span class="author">Eric Sim</span><span class="separator">/</span>
      <time datetime="2026-03-22">March 22, 2026</time><span class="separator">/</span>
      <span>10 min read</span>
    </div>
  </header>

  <figure class="article-featured-image">
    <div class="image-placeholder">[ featured: DanBam restaurant from Itaewon Class, exterior at night ]</div>
    <figcaption>The real DanBam location from Itaewon Class in Itaewon, Seoul. Photo: Eric Sim / The Hansang</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <div class="article-layout">
    <article class="article-content">

      <p>Korean dramas have a way of making food look impossibly good. The ramyeon scene in Parasite. The fried chicken and beer in My Love from the Star. The street food montage in Reply 1988.</p>

      <p>So we did. Over two trips to Seoul in 2025 and early 2026, we tracked down the real restaurants featured in some of the most popular K-dramas of the past decade.</p>

      <p>Here is what we found.</p>

      <h2>Itaewon Class: DanBam (Danbam Pocha)</h2>
      <p>The bar-restaurant from Itaewon Class is real. The actual filming location is on a side street in Itaewon, and while the original DanBam signage is gone, the building is recognizable.</p>
      <figure class="inline-photo"><div class="image-placeholder">[ photo: the DanBam building in Itaewon ]</div><figcaption>Left: the real DanBam building in Itaewon today. Right: a still from Itaewon Class.</figcaption></figure>

      <h2>My Love from the Star: The Pojangmacha</h2>
      <p>The iconic pojangmacha scene turned chimaek into a cultural phenomenon across Asia. For the authentic pojangmacha experience, head to Euljiro 3-ga.</p>

      <h2>Reply 1988: Ssangmun-dong</h2>
      <p>Reply 1988 is set in the Ssangmun-dong neighbourhood of northern Seoul, and much of the show's warmth comes from the neighbourhood itself.</p>
      <figure class="inline-photo"><div class="image-placeholder">[ photo: narrow alleyway in Ssangmun-dong ]</div><figcaption>The real Ssangmun-dong neighbourhood in northern Seoul.</figcaption></figure>

      <aside class="ad-inline" aria-label="Advertisement"><div class="ad-slot"><span class="ad-slot-label">Partner</span>Advertisement</div></aside>

      <h2>Hometown Cha-Cha-Cha: Pohang and Yeongdeok</h2>
      <p>The seaside village in Hometown Cha-Cha-Cha is based on a real fishing village near Pohang on Korea's east coast.</p>

      <h2>Crash Landing on You: The Chicken Shop</h2>
      <p>The fried chicken shop that Yoon Se-ri frequents is based on real locations in both Seoul and the Swiss village of Iseltwald.</p>

      <aside class="ad-inline" aria-label="Advertisement"><div class="ad-slot"><span class="ad-slot-label">Partner</span>Advertisement</div></aside>

